News Headline:
Ouch, the Bill for ObamaCare Coming Due
The bill is coming due for ObamaCare, and it's a whopper. 
According to Medicare's actuaries, U.S. health care spending is about to skyrocket. 
ObamaCare continues federal meddling in what was once the finest and cost-effective health care system on the planet is nothing new. 
Back in the 1960s, many Americans paid for doctor and hospital services out of pocket or through modestly priced private insurance.
Health care spending was about 6% of the country's gross domestic product. 
Enter President Lyndon B. Johnson and Medicare. He bought millions of votes by giving seniors free health care that they never paid for through payroll taxes during their working years. He also helped lay the foundations for the entitlement state with Medicaid. 
Medicaid, which was conceived to help poor children, has been gradually expanded to include many working families. ( all government programs are ever-expanding; they never get smaller)
Today health care spending is more than 17% of GDP,  almost 3 times more expensive than it used to be.
Germany and Holland spend about 12% and have about the same coverage that we do.
The extra costs in the U.S. are federally mandated giveaways, inefficiencies and abuse -- about $850 billion
NOTE: The  $850 Billion  that our federal government WASTES in Medicare/Medicaid, is  more than we spend on our entire military.
Think about that.
Federal programs set reimbursements for providers and limit use of many drugs and procedures. Those rules are intended to mirror market prices and informed private decisions but often do not. 
No bureaucratic rule or computer program can even capture all the judgments we put into purchasing decisions to maximize what we squeeze from our incomes to meet our family's needs.
Those decisions build up to become what economists call the invisible hand of the marketplace that guides businesses to make what we need. 
Just as Soviet central planning failed to put enough TVs and beef on store shelves, federally managed health care creates long waits to see doctors and lots of opportunities for 'soft' fraud -- activities by health care providers that game federal rules -- and outright stealing. 
Once again:  the  'gaming of the rules' the  'soft fraud'  and the 'outright  stealing' that are going on within our Federal Government  in the  Medicare and Medicaid programs  adds up to MORE  than the cost of our entire  military.
WTF ??

NEWS  HEADLINE:
IRS finds more key hard-drive crashes, claims no evidence of tampering.  ( I just love this,  IRS is investigating itself and  OOPS !!  More hard drive crashes !!  )
The Internal Revenue Service is missing e-mails from five more employees whose records could shed light on the agency's targeting scandal, but there are no signs that personnel have intentionally destroyed evidence, according to an IRS review.  ( Do you believe that one ?) 
In a report to four congressional committees on Friday, the IRS said hard-drive crashes are to blame for the lost communications. The agency added that the computer malfunctions "appear to be the same sorts of issues routinely experienced within the IRS, in other government agencies and in the private sector."  (  Routinely experienced when there is an urgent need to cover Obama's lying ass )
The report also noted that the crashes occurred before the start of investigations into how the agency identified nonprofit advocacy groups for extra scrutiny. The IRS's inspector general released an audit last year that said the agency inappropriately targeted certain organizations based on their names and policy positions.
The IRS notified Congress earlier this year that it is missing a years worth of e-mails from Lois Lerner, the ex-agency official whose department was at the center of the targeting scandal. Lerner retired from the government in September 2013, about four months after acknowledging her office's mistakes.
IRS chief John Koskinen testified at a hearing in June that the agency lost many of Lerner's e-mail records after her hard-drive crashed in 2011. ( A crash that didn't really happen )  He said the agency tried unsuccessfully to recover the data and then sent the broken device away for destruction.  ( Which we now know is not true, another lie ) 
The IRS said in its report on Friday that the agency now knows of five more employees who are missing e-mails because of hard-drive crashes. The staff members include: Judy Kindell, who was Lerner's former senior adviser; IRS tax-law specialist Justin Lowe, who worked with Kindell; IRS manager Ron Shoemaker, who helped oversee the cases in question; and two Cincinnati-based IRS employees who had worked on some of the cases. ( All the people involved in the IRS probe who covered for Obama vote Democrat )
The agency said all of the employees contacted IT staff and attempted to recover their data after their computers malfunctioned. ( No malfunction;  they worked perfectly well, right up to the point that they might implicate Obama and Lois Lerner )
The IRS said in a recent court filing that it also "removed or wiped clean" information from Lerner's Blackberry in June 2012, after congressional staffers began questioning her -- and in the same month that TIGTA began its review of the matter. The mobile device may have contained duplicates of Lerner's missing e-mails.  ( All wiped clean,  per direct orders from Obama )
RELATED: Why did the IRS clean out Lois Lerner's Blackberry as probes began?  ( To protect Obama ) 
The IRS has not explained why it erased information from Lerner's Blackberry in June 2012.   ( To protect Obama ) 
Republicans have suggested that the Obama administration used the IRS to hinder emerging conservative and tea party groups during the past two election cycles, when the agency used the inappropriate screening methods.  ( Obviously )
Democrats have rejected that theory.  ( Of course )
The Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations issued a report last week saying it found "no evidence of IRS political bias" in the IRS's targeting actions. ( To protect Obama )
Republicans are saying the TIGTA audit was "accurate and proper" and that 83 percent of the groups that the IRS pulled aside for extra scrutiny were conservative.

post_title: Who are you, and who are your neighbors?
post_text:
I have not posted for some time, and am disappointed upon my return to see the types of posts in this column.
A friend of mine used to say, "when the herd gets overpopulated, the animals get weird. . ."  Never truer than today.   Resources are scarce and expensive, jobs are few and low paying.  As a society, our stress level is at an all-time high.  
A man at the supermarket raised his voice to the deli clerk, "Eight bucks!  You're kidding, right?  I have to get a pound, do you not get that?"  The bewildered and powerless deli clerk was speechless.   A guy with a pair of jumper cables in the Denny's parking lot approached a man returning to his car, he was greeted with, "get the hell away from me."  A septuagenarian lady in line at the pharmacy complained about the price of her prescription.  Heard from the line, "not like you'll need them much longer anyway."
Humans are an omnivorous pack animal.  Like all pack animals, when resources become scarce the pack sticks closer together in order to consolidate efforts for procuring food and shelter.  Our society is reacting in the same manner, we are so highly polarized we are quick to accuse and call out anyone that is not from our immediate "pack."  We've given each other new derogatory handles, Democants, Republicrats, sheeple, etc.  We've even revived some archaic labels such as redneck and porch monkey.   Politicizing is the new racism.  The next step is obvious.
Nature demonstrates that when a pack is stressed enough, they begin to eliminate both their weaker members and any rival packs that are competing for resources.  They will either drive them off our outright kill them.  As a species, we humans have repeatedly demonstrated we have the full capacity for this behavior model.   How long do we have?  No one knows, but I'd venture it will begin shortly after the first stone is thrown.  Right now, we're only parrying, verbal jabs back and forth, derogatory labels, denigrating our fellow man.  We're testing the waters, you see, yipping like jackals at prey.
As a species divided into secular, tribal groups, we don't stand a chance.  The more we objectify and denigrate our fellow man, the more we buy into our own demise.  The more we embrace the "us vs. them," philosophy, the greater likelihood that we ourselves will wind up living in caves, clubbing each other for a piece of meat.
"I know not with what weapons World War III will be fought, but World War IV will be fought with sticks and stones."
Albert Einstein

Your post is below...  I'm not sure I get your points.  If 10% of the US Farmers actually collect 75% of the subsidies, how much of that do you suppose your small-time farming neighbors there are actually getting???  I'd say none.  I'd bet the lions share of that goes to the conglomerates, ADM and the Nebraska Mob, etc.  ADM by the way is arab owned if you dig deep enough...
Also, I'd scratch my head on your source's stated cost increases on both fruit and sodas.  Your research showed 30 and 34% since the 1970's, I don't think that's correct and think it is WAY higher.  In the 1970's gas was 68 cents a gallon, now diesel is around four bucks.  Fuel for machinery is a substantial expense in farming.  Friends of mine farm nuts, they mentioned that their costs since mid-2000 have gone up by around 35% just in that short time frame.  
I think the deal with corn/sorghum feeding cattle is more complex, too.  For instance, we used to grow alfalfa twenty years ago.  It took ALOT of water.  In a good year, we'd get three cuttings a season.  Cows have to eat something...  They're now selling alfalfa for like $15 bucks a bale, we used to sell it for two.  I know a guy and his wife that have a really large cattle ranch in north Nevada.  They grew their own alfalfa down in New Mexico and trucked it to their range in Nevada, a water deal between New Mexico and Texas put the kibosh on that... so no more alfalfa.  They're now buying it for winter feed, but have to supplement with corn and milo.  Alfalfa really isn't a practical crop to grow anymore for feed.  It takes too much land, too much water, and in the end you don't get that much usable feed for what you tie up in it.  The biggest clincher is the amount of water it takes.
Farming in Germany is really cool.  Everything is so organized and really well done.  Most watering is underground.  You can't do that for alfalfa though.  They also feed cattle corn and milo.  
I guess in a perfect world, all cattle would graze free-range on natural grasses.  That can't be done anymore either.  We've overpopulated this planet to the point that we don't have enough grassland to feed them.  If you are really, really lucky and have good dependable grass fields, you can feed 1 cow per three acres of land during the summer/growing season only.  Then you have to supplement in the winter with either alfalfa (super expensive) or corn/milo.  In most of the US that is left, you may be able to feed one cow per 20 acres of range land.  Some of the dryer areas, you have to dedicate like 100 acres per cow (no kidding).  That would take like a gozillion acres to feed like, 1000 cows.
I'm astounded with all our chemical engineering, they cannot engineer a protien substance that's free of toxins as a food source.  Doesn't sound appetizing, I know...  But..  I've seen some cool research on sea kelp and other sources that may be promising.  The real deal on that is, though...  how long until we start to run out of that??

Rural America is usually painted as a pastoral scene of rolling cropland and family farms. But increasingly, this historic landscape is threatened by the harsh reality of factory farms. Also known as Concentrated Animal Feeding Operations, Confined Animal Feeding Operations, or CAFOs, factory farms use industrial production techniques to raise thousands of animals in one location.
This type of industrial agriculture is increasingly how the agribusiness industry is meeting our country's demand for beef, pork, and poultry. The EPA has estimated there are now more than 20,000 factory farms nationwide, a 30 percent rise since 2003 1. The American Public Health Association estimates that 54 percent of livestock in the country is now confined on just 5 percent of livestock farms.2  This relatively new model of livestock production has grown rapidly since the early 1990s. The Government Accountability Office estimates that the number of CAFOs in the U.S. more than tripled between 1982 and 2002.3 The growth in factory farms has forced thousands of independent farmers out of business by decreasing the sale price of animals. In the hog industry, for example, about one quarter of all U.S. producers went out of business between 1998 and 2000, leaving only 50 producers controlling onehalf of all hog production.4

post_title: I will tell you about homelessness around here
post_text:
About 5 or 6 years ago I knew there was a life lesson I needed to find, and I went hitchhiking to find it, I didn't do it because I had no choice, or because I was too lazy to work, but because there was a new experience to be had and something to learn.  When I got to Humboldt I could not leave, how could I leave a place of such beauty and awesome weather!  After almost 2 years on the streets I got to know pretty much every homeless person around, most of them are great people with very sad pasts, most never learned how to cope in life the way most of us do, and most end up being alcoholics.  
It is very hard for someone that has never been in that position to understand, let alone the weight of a life of horrible situations I could never fathom.  Humboldt is an interesting place, a place with free thinkers, true individuals, and a fascinating black market that literally dominates the core of this county economically.  This leads to interesting mix of people including a lot of people that seem homeless but really are just traveling cogs in the weed industry, and of course you also get the people that let themselves get so low that they will steel from their own grandmother to tweak out a bit more.
Now let us move on to people such as myself, who am I?   I think my little post here shows I am obviously educated (It seriously saddens me how bad grammar has gotten in this country), in-fact most of my working life has been spent doing computer programming, and the last 2 dedicated to electronics engineering, and here I am only weeks away from homelessness, been living a hotel for a month now trying to find a job, and I can't find one.  What does that say?   Here I am with plenty of skills and I cannot find work.  The chance is higher I will be homeless again soon then not be, and not for a lack of trying.  I have had 5 interviews since trying to get back on my feet, yet no one hires me why?  I will tell you why, you don't get job offers if you don't have a car and a steady life, which is pretty counter-productive to me since it would seem the person that is homeless or about to be homeless NEEDS the job more then the guy with the lifted truck, a house, and 6 months of savings to fall on, but that is the person who will get the job every time.
You anti-homeless need to get off your high horse and start thinking about your community more then yourself, take a look at the world, we are on the brink of WW3, and the world economy is already in it's death bed, and I will tell you what, you will find a lot more homeless around soon, many people who once thought it could never be them, and if that time comes to you and I hope it never does, then remember how you once looked at the homeless when you are in the same position. 
And remember, home is where the heart is.

post_title: Seeking woman who appreciates Tiki culture, Mid
post_text:
Life is too short for superficial pursuits, and I feel dating in this city is mostly a thinly-veiled form of power-brokering. However, I know there are genuine people out there who are also seeking something real.
I'm looking for someone that I can eventually call my best friend, my lover, my wife. Someone with whom I can watch a movie at home, travel and explore or have a three hour long conversation about politics, literature, music, the nature of existence or the challenges of cultivating and sustaining Love.
I was born in Hollywood and have lived in California my whole life, so I'm one of those rare, fabled natives you might've heard about from time to time.
I'm college educated. I have a degree in literature from UC Berkeley. I love to read, write, watch movies--especially anything black-and-white, Italian or Japanese. Kurosawa is my favorite. I love Shakespeare, Kurt Vonnegut, Nathaniel Hawthorne, J.D. Salinger (RIP), the dictionary.
My parents are still married, so I take marriage seriously. I would rather have a quiet, meaningful ceremony and a lasting marriage as opposed to a $100,000 wedding and a mediocre marriage.
I love the outdoors, especially mountain hiking. I like the beach, too, but probably take it for granted since it was always so close. But my favorite climate is the desert, which I'd be happy to explain because I usually have to qualify that statement.
I love to travel. I spent a month in Siberia and another five months traveling throughout most of Europe. It changed me in a dramatic way. Everyone in Siberia was dirt poor, but I will never forget that they were the happiest group of people I have EVER seen. I really want to travel to Japan. I am a little obsessed with Japanese culture and just started to learn the language, though my skill level is still up for debate.
I was a strict vegetarian for 12 years, though I have recently started to eat seafood. I love to cook, but I try to avoid processed foods, sodas or anything with high fructose corn syrup, MSG or any other ingredient I cannot pronounce.
Lots of things make me smile: animals (especially whenever a dog smiles), people who signal when they turn, random politeness, a movie without digital effects, modesty in the face of fame, a home-cooked meal, people returning your hello when walking past, improv comedy; pristine, hard-to-find records, passing a good book on to a friend, receiving a good book from a friend, sushi, music that touches the soul, and basically anyone that puts love into their work and into their lives.
My aspirations have always been to be a story-teller. I feel story-telling is akin to religion. I have been inspired, and practically rescued, by good stories.
I have been working in the motion picture business for 14 years now. I am a title/graphic designer. Though I had always wanted to direct movies, being in the film business has afforded me the opportunity to see that I want out. I have focused most of my free time on writing novels. I have no illusions about the lack of income they generate, but one can dream, right?
Realistically, I would like to go back to school and earn a teaching credential and a master's degree so I can teach literature and film history at the community college level.
My most embarrassing moment? It's a good one. About 15 years ago, I was at a party with a friend of mine, and I was talking to this really nice, cute and intelligent girl in the backyard. I was feeling pretty good about the conversation. I went back into the house to grab a drink, but I neglected to see the screen door was still closed. So, I walked straight through the doorway, taking out the screen door entirely from the frame, knocking it to the floor and landing on top of it. Needless to say, I basically ran out of the house and waited for my friend (who was my ride) to come out front and haul my sorry ass away...far, far away.
One afternoon while I was still in high school, I was hanging out with four of my friends. We were at a thrift store. As I waited alone outside for my friends, this really old man collapsed in front of me. He was bleeding and flailing helplessly on the ground, so I helped him up. I asked if he needed help home or if I could call someone for him (obviously this was long before cel phones). He just paused, looked me in the face and said, "I have no one." He said it so earnestly and so matter-of-factly that this overwhelming loneliness poured over me, and I vowed I would never be in that position when I was his age.
So, ultimately, I am looking for someone that, again, can be my best friend. Someone who won't judge me for my faults, someone who won't take advantage of me, someone who will help me when things aren't going so well, someone who will accept my help when things aren't going so well for her, someone who laughs at the same twisted things that make me laugh, someone who will cry when beauty strikes her, someone who can just look at me and catch the subtlety of my emotion just from glancing into my eyes...
